LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF IDAHO
Sixty-eighth Legislature First Regular Session - 2025
IN THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
HOUSE BILL NO. 378
BY STATE AFFAIRS COMMITTEE
1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO TRANSPARENT AND ETHICAL GOVERNMENT; AMENDING TITLE 74, IDAHO
3 CODE, BY THE ADDITION OF A NEW CHAPTER 7, TITLE 74, IDAHO CODE, TO
4 PROVIDE LEGISLATIVE INTENT AND TO PROVIDE FOR REPORTING OF PAID LEG-
5 ISLATIVE TRAVEL AND A PENALTY; AND DECLARING AN EMERGENCY AND PROVIDING
6 AN EFFECTIVE DATE.
7 Be It Enacted by the Legislature of the State of Idaho:
8 SECTION 1. That Title 74, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby amended
9 by the addition thereto of a NEW CHAPTER, to be known and designated as Chap-
10 ter 7, Title 74, Idaho Code, and to read as follows:
11 CHAPTER 7
12 TRANSPARENCY IN LEGISLATIVE TRAVEL
13 74-701. LEGISLATIVE INTENT. It is the intent of the legislature to
14 promote public confidence in government and to promote transparency by
15 requiring legislators, legislators-elect, and candidates for legislative
16 office to report travel paid for by others.
17 74-702. REPORTING OF PAID TRAVEL -- PENALTY. (1) All legislative offi-
18 cials shall report to the secretary of state all travel outside of Idaho rea-
19 sonably related to a legislative or governmental purpose or to an issue of
20 state, national, or international public policy paid for by another individ-
21 ual or entity. Travel paid through campaign funds that are reported pursuant
22 to chapter 66, title 67, Idaho Code, or solely through personal funds of a
23 legislative official shall not be subject to the requirements of this sec-
24 tion. For the purposes of this section, "legislative official" means a leg-
25 islative candidate who will appear on a general election ballot, a member of
26 the Idaho legislature, and a member-elect of the Idaho legislature who has
27 prevailed in a general election but has not yet received the oath of office.
28 (2) Within thirty (30) days of the return date of any travel subject to
29 the provisions of subsection (1) of this section, a legislative official who
30 is subject to the reporting requirements provided for in subsection (1) of
31 this section shall file a report with the secretary of state that includes:
32 (a) The travel destination;
33 (b) The dates of travel;
34 (c) The purpose of the travel; and
35 (d) The name and address of the person or entity that paid for the
36 travel, including whether the travel was a campaign contribution and,
37 in the case of current members of the legislature, whether the travel
38 was made in such member's official capacity as a legislator.
39 (3) Any legislative official who fails to file the report required pur-
40 suant to subsection (2) of this section within thirty (30) days shall be sub-

2
1 ject to a late fee in the amount of twenty-five dollars ($25.00) each day un-
2 til the report is filed, which fee shall be deposited in the public school in-
3 come fund.
4 SECTION 2. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
5 declared to exist, this act shall be in full force and effect on and after
6 July 1, 2025.

